Job Specification


UNEMPLOYMENT INSURANCE TECHNICIAN 4    DEFINITION:Under the general supervision of a Supervisory official in the Department  of Labor and Workforce Development, is directly responsible for all  communications systems which provide general and technical information  and instructions to the public and to operational units of the Divisions of  Unemployment and Disability Insurance; is responsible for the supervision  of a unit of Unemployment Insurance Technicians and other employees  involved in improving the quality and effectiveness of unemployment and  disability insurance operations; does related work as required.NOTE:  The examples of work for this title are for illustrative purposes only.   A particular position using this title may not perform all duties listed in this job specification.  Conversely all duties performed on the job may not be listed. EXAMPLES OF WORKSupervises the development, implementation and maintenance of procedures,  manuals, guides, forms and reports used in processing unemployment and  disability insurance claims, particularly those inherent to the Local Office  On-Line Payment System (LOOPS) and/or the Disability Automated Benefit  System (DABS), and other related tax service systems.Reviews program letters from the federal government; takes necessary  action to ensure that benefits and tax operations are in line with federal  requirements, standards, regulations and policies.Supervises technicians and other personnel and assigns tasks to unit  members and gives technical advice and assistance in order to facilitate  completion of necessary functions.Supervises the work operations and/or functional programs and has  responsibility for effectively recommending the hiring, firing, promoting,  demoting and/or disciplining of employees.Drafts proposed changes in the Unemployment and Disability Insurance  laws and Employment Security Rules and Regulations based on specific  knowledge of the problems encountered in operating the various programs  under the jurisdiction of the Division.Reviews all legislative bills and newly enacted laws and federal programs  to assess their impact on the administration of these programs, both  operationally and fiscally. Writes detailed reports on findings and makes  recommendations, as required, to the Director.Supervises the organization, planning and implementation of the federal  UI Quality Appraisal program and the officeï¿½s evaluations of benefit, appeal  and tax functions; analyzes operational problems uncovered by the  appraisals and evaluations; takes and/or recommends necessary corrective  action.Supervises the writing of new informational publications; reviews and/or  supervises the review of all current publications to ensure their accuracy  in terms of law, rules and regulations,  and program changes; issues  revisions as needed, writes and/or supervises the writing of reports.Supervises the writing of extensive, technical correspondence, requiring  full knowledge of all phases of unemployment and disability insurance  programs and administrative policy.Assigns subordinate staff to the various functions and oversees the  distribution of work. Directs the writing of bulletins and Administrative Memoranda which serve  to keep staff in the Division aware of changes in Federal and State laws,  rules, regulations and procedures, handles inquiries from Local, District  and Central Offices regarding interpretation of operating manuals and  guidelines.Supervises the planning and development of training programs; participates  in Federal and State training seminars.As required, represents Assistant Director at meetings, makes report on  matters discussed.Coordinates periodic inspections of offices to review entire office processes.Supervises the review of existing procedures to ensure compliance with  Federal and State guidelines. Recommends corrective action and reports  results to Assistant Director or Bureau Chief.Supervises and/or participates in the implementation of the Unemployment  Insurance Account Executive Program.Supervises the gathering of technical information regarding UI and  Disability benefits for attorneys, police, FBI and other Federal agencies.Supervises the coordination of activities between UI-DI and other public  agencies, including Eligibility Review Program, Citizens' Complaints Unit  of the Public Advocate's Office, and UI Employability Program in conjunction  with the Employment Service.Confers with the office of the Attorney General and other legal authorities  in order to resolve legal questions which relate to the interpretation and  enforcement of statutes.Maintains the essential records and files.Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and computerized information system used by the agency, office,  or related units. REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Eight (8) years of professional experience in work involving various phases of social insurance such as disability, unemployment or workers compensation programs in a public or private agency.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and four (4) years of the above-mentioned professional experience.ORPossession of a Master's degree in Business or Public Administration or related area from an accredited college or university; and three (3) years of the above-mentioned professional experience.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:Knowledge of principles of supervision and their application in office  operations, including factors which affect employees' performance such  as motivation, personality and work assignment.Knowledge of methods used to evaluate the efficiency of programs.Knowledge of the problems faced in auditing, analyzing and evaluating  office operations and in instituting necessary corrective measures.Knowledge of business terminology and technical know-how to draft  documents.Knowledge of statistical methods and devices as they apply to  New Jersey Unemployment Compensation Law.Knowledge of the rules, regulations, policies, and procedures of the  Division of Unemployment and Disability Insurance.Knowledge of New Jersey Unemployment Compensation Law,  related  Federal statutes, New Jersey Temporary Disability Benefits Law, and  related Executive orders. Knowledge of Civil Service Rules, Departmental regulations and policies  concerning personnel matters and the terms of the various Union  Agreements applicable.Knowledge of the supervisory problems related to the operation of all  phases of the unemployment and disability insurance program in the  central and local office.Knowledge of all procedures related to all phases of the Local Office  On-Line Payment System.Ability to draft changes in the unemployment and disability insurance  laws and rules which are legally binding and in accordance with the  objectives of the Division.Ability to provide technical advice and assistance to line and staff  officials of the Division on matters relating to management and  systems requirementsAbility to write and/or supervise the writing of informational publications  for the various public served by the Division.Ability to analyze and evaluate or supervise evaluations of unemployment  insurance activities, including tax and benefit functions, and formulate  recommendations for new and/or revised programs, procedures and  forms to ensure efficient operations.Ability to establish and maintain cooperative relationships or direct  technicians of a lower level in the establishment and maintenance of  cooperative relationships with other services and bureaus within the  Division and with related federal and State agencies.Ability to acquire the knowledge of supervisory methods and techniques.Ability to take and maintain a firm and correct stand when differences  of opinion arise.Ability to compose or supervise the composition of official and technical  correspondence.Ability to prepare clear, sound, accurate and informative reports of a  technical nature containing findings, conclusions and formal recommendations.Ability to prepare presentations and address groups.Ability to maintain the essential records and files.Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and manual recording and information systems used by the agency, office,  or related units.Ability to read, write, speak, understand, and communicate in English sufficiently to perform duties of this position.  American Sign Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of communication.Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long As they can perform essential functions of the job with or without  reasonable accommodation.  If the accommodation cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue hardship, such persons  may not be eligible.CODE:  56105   08/24/2013

