CHIEF AUDIT ACTIVITY TREASURY    DEFINITION:Under the direction of a supervisory official in the Department of the Treasury, plans, organizes and directs the work programs involving  audit and/or accounting and budget activities; provides guidance and  direction to senior management with respect to Division matters; does  related work as required.NOTE:  The examples of work for this title are for illustrative purposes  only.  A particular position using this title may not perform all duties  listed in this job specification.  Conversely, all duties performed on the job may not be listed. EXAMPLES OF WORKIn the Division of Taxation, directs the following functions through an  Assistant Chief Auditor, Taxation, and/or group of supervisors of Audit  personnel: the field audits and/or office audits of returns and supporting  documents to determine correct tax liability and of claims to determine  allowability of refunds; the preparation of reports supported by explanations,  citations and authority on cases where adjustments are made, and  appropriate reports on no change cases, or information reports, as required;  and other audits made at request of the Legal Staff or the Attorney General,  including joint operations in cases where tax evasion or fraud may exist.In the Division of Pensions, plans, coordinates and directs the accounting  activities and staff of the Accounting Services, which is responsible for  accounting activities related to Employee Benefit Programs such as the  Public Employees Retirement System; Teachersï¿½ Pension and Annuity  Fund; Police and Firemen's Retirement System; the State Agency for  Social Security; Prison Officers Pension Fund; State Police Retirement  System; Judicial Retirement System; Alternate Benefit Program; Central  Pension Fund; Pension Increase Program; the Supplemental Annuity  Collective Trust; Health Benefits Program; the State Employee Prescription  Drug Program and such units as the Adjustment and Bookkeeping Sections.Plans, organizes and directs the activities of the agency; sets goals and  plans; implements work programs and develops policies and procedures  in accordance with division policies and goals.Supervises the development of work plans for all activities within the  agency; modifies and adapts plans, as required.Responsible for implementing new or revised Federal and State laws,  regulations, and reporting procedures as they apply to the various State  programs.Manages the work operations and/or functional programs and has  responsibility for employee evaluations and for effectively recommending the  hiring, firing, promoting, demoting, disciplining and/or training of employees.Directs the development of data processing, telecommunications and  other on-line procedures with the various vendors and is directly  responsible for their implementation.Assesses the impact of new or revised legislation and policy changes  on agency operations; recommends amendments to existing or proposed  legislation to improve the effectiveness of program operations.Monitors results of program efforts through development of appropriate  measurement devices and establishment of tracking systems.Evaluates program operations and performance; as required, develops  and implements alternative procedures to improve performance and meet  program objectives.Develops, reviews and submits the annual agency budget for approval.Represents the division and testifies at appeal hearings, when  designated by senior management.Assists senior management in the development of planning systems  and methods to improve coordination of activities and integration of  client services.Estimates future workloads and required personnel space and equipment  to achieve the objectives of agency programs.Prepares and delivers presentations, speeches and testimonies before  professional and lay groups and supervises the dissemination of program  information to inquiring employers, employees and other individuals and  groups.Develops and/or supervises the preparation, update, and/or maintenance  of agency procedures manuals, administrative regulations and guidelines,  benefits manuals, booklets and other information materials distributed to  the public.Implements, monitors, and maintains policies of sound fiscal management  and ensures conformity of Division rules and regulations with those of the  State and other Departments; works with executive level management  toward maximizing economies of agency purchases.Performs special projects, as directed by executive management.Serves as a principal advisor to senior management with respect to agency  activities including coordination required with other interagency units.Coordinates the work of the agency with the work of the other operational  and support agencies in the division.Reviews, analyzes, and interprets Federal and State laws, rules, and  regulations affecting the operation of the agency.Responsible for the preparation and presentation of monthly and  quarterly statistical reports and data reflecting the activities and  productivity of the agency.Prepares and/or directs the preparation of extensive correspondence  in the course of official duties.Prepares and supervises the preparation of technically sound, accurate  and informative statistical, financial, and other reports, letters and  documents containing findings, conclusions and recommendations.Directs the establishment and maintenance of essential records,  reports, files and data sources.Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or  manual recording and information systems used by the agency,  office, or related units.  REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Ten (10) years of professional auditing or accounting experience in performing audits including writing the accompanying audit report and/or the complete review and examination of tax returns for propriety, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity, including or supplemented by twenty-one (21) semester hour credits in accounting.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university, including or supplemented by twenty-one (21) semester hour credits in accounting; and six (6) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORA valid certificate as a Certified Public Accountant (CPA) issued by the New Jersey State Board of Public Accountants;  and six (6) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a Master's degree in Accounting or Business Administration from an accredited college or university; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIESKnowledge of the design, installation and operation of a large scale  accounting program.Knowledge of the procedures used in keeping detailed accounts of  financial transactions and in preparing, checking and interpreting  varied financial statements.Knowledge of modern accounting principles, standards and  techniques and their application to specific accounting situations.Knowledge of the methods used to interpret varied types of financial  data and of the proper form of financial documents, statements and  schedules.Knowledge of the methods used to prepare detailed accounting  and other financial reports containing findings, conclusions and  recommendations.Knowledge of the types of discrepancies found in financial records,  and the methods used in preventing, discovering and correcting errors.Knowledge of supervisory techniques.Ability to organize assigned work and develop an appropriate work  program and schedules for the agency.Ability to plan, direct, and coordinate the work of the assigned units,  including setting goals, planning and implementing work programs and developing policies and procedures.Ability to develop long and short term management plans and  procedures, and to develop effective methods.Ability to understand, analyze, and interpret basic laws and regulations,  and apply them to specific situations.Ability to evaluate program or unit performance and develop alternative  methods to improve performance and meet established objectives.Ability to establish and maintain effective working relationships with  representatives of Federal, State and local governments, as well as  professional groups, and others interested in issues, problems, and  topics relative to designated program.Ability to assign, instruct and supervise professional, technical,  and other employees and to effectively evaluate their performance.Ability to supervise the compilation of needed statistical data.Ability to prepare extensive correspondence in the course of official  duties.Ability to prepare and supervise the preparation of clear, sound, technically accurate and informative reports containing findings,  conclusions and recommendations.Ability to direct the establishment and maintenance of essential  records and files.Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and information systems used by the agency, office or  related units.Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in English  sufficiently to perform the duties of this position.  American Sign  Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of  communication.Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long as  they can perform the essential functions of the job with or without  reasonable accommodation.  If the accommodation cannot be made  because it would cause the employer undue hardship, such persons  may not be eligible. This job specification is applicable to the following title code:JobSpecCodeVariantState,Local orCommonClass ofServiceWorkWeekStateClassCodeLocalClassCodeSalaryRangeNote61060SCNL33N/A&33

