CHIEF DIVISION OF PENSIONS    DEFINITION:        Under the general direction of the Director or other senior   management officer in the Division of Pensions, Department of the   Treasury, plans, directs, coordinates and administers the work   programs, activities and staff of a bureau; provides guidance and   direction to senior management in the development and recommendation of   policies and procedures applicable to Bureau operations; does related   work as required.  EXAMPLES OF WORK:        Plans, organizes, and directs the activities of the Bureau; sets   goals and plans; implements work programs and develops policies and   procedures in accordance with division policies and goals.       Supervises the development of work plans for all activities within   the Bureau; modifies and adapts plans, as required.       Directly responsible for implementing new or revised federal and   state laws, regulations, and reporting procedures as they apply to the   various state programs.       Manages the work operations and/or functional programs, and has   responsibility for employee evaluation, and for effectively   recommending the hiring, firing, promoting, demoting and/or   disciplining of employees.       Supervises various levels of professional and technical employees,   and evaluates the performance of their work.       Directs the development of data processing, telecommunications and   other on-line procedures with the various vendors, and is directly   responsible for their implementation.       Serves as a principal advisor to senior management with respect to   Bureau activities including coordination required with other Bureaus.       Coordinates the work of the Bureau with the work of the other   operational and support Bureaus in the division.  benefit structures and administrative practices.       Reviews, analyzes, and interprets federal and state laws, rules   and regulations affecting the operation of the Bureau.       In the Administrative Services Bureau, organizes and coordinates   the Division's staffing personnel requirements while directing and   controlling the preparation of personnel documents; provides liaison   with the State Treasurer's Administrative offices and the Department of   Personnel.       In the Administrative Services Bureau, organizes and coordinates   the activities of the Division's three administrative offices and two   warehouse facilities and related staff; engages in space and site   acquisition, vehicles, supplies, and equipment; plans and directs all   related support services to insure continuity of the Division's   operations.       In the Administrative Services Bureau, plans and conducts space   and layout studies to ensure efficient utilization of buildings and   grounds.  Analyzes current and projected staffing and warehouse   requirements and recommends physical and location needs.  Coordinates   the acquisition of property needs, and supervises the relocation   operation.       Responsible for the preparation and presentation of monthly and   quarterly statistical reports and data reflecting the activities and   productivity of the Bureau.       Prepares and/or directs the preparation of extensive   correspondence in the course of official duties.       Prepares and supervises the preparation of technically sound,   accurate, and informative statistical, financial, and other reports,   letters and documents containing findings, conclusions, and   recommendations.       Directs the establishment and maintenance of essential records,   reports, files and data source.       May be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic   and/or manual recording and information systems used by the Bureau or   Division.   REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Nine (9) years of professional administrative experience in a public or private group employee insurance, retirement, or pension system; two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.      OR Possession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, two (2) years which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.  OR  Possession of  Master's degree in Business Administration, Public  Administration, Management or other relevant field; and four (4) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:           Knowledge of modern management concepts and practices.           Knowledge of, planning principles, practices, and procedures,   organization theory, and administrative practices to the program.           Knowledge of the functions, responsibilities, regulations and   procedures established to administer pertinent statutes and their   application to specific situations.           Knowledge of the problems involved in the administration of   benefits programs including the enrollment, collection and auditing,   and claims administration aspects of such programs.            Knowledge of the principles and practices of supervision,   employee motivation, and performance evaluation.           Ability to acquire knowledge of the laws of New Jersey and the   regulations promulgated thereunder pertaining to public employee's   pensions and other employee benefit program.           Ability to acquire knowledge of the priorities, programs,   objectives, policies, and the internal organization of the Division.           Ability to organize assigned technical and supervisory work,   and develop an appropriate work program and schedules for the Bureau.           Ability to plan, direct, and coordinate the work of the   assigned units, including setting goals, planning, and implementing   work programs, and developing policies and procedures.           Ability to develop long and short term management plans and   procedures and develop effective methods.           Ability to understand, analyze, interpret, and apply basic law   and regulations to employee benefit work in accordance with the   provisions of the statute.           Ability to coordinate the work of the bureau with that of   other bureaus and administrative units within the division.           Ability to evaluate program or unit performance, and develop   alternative methods to improve performance and meet established   objectives.           Ability to give oral presentations to, and establish and   maintain effective working relationships with, representatives of   federal, state and local governments, as well as professional groups,   and others interested in issues, problems, and topics relative to   designated program.           Ability to assign, instruct, and supervise professional   technical, and other employees, and to effectively evaluate their   performance.           Ability to supervise the compilation of needed statistical   data.           Ability to draft extensive correspondence in the course of   official duties.           Ability to prepare and supervise the preparation of clear,   sound, technically accurate, and informative reports containing   findings, conclusions, and recommendations.           Ability to direct the establishment and maintenance of   essential records and files.           Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or   manual recording and information systems used by the agency, office, or   related units.           Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in   English sufficiently to perform the duties of this position.  American   Sign Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of   communication.           Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as   long as they can perform the essential functions of the job after   reasonable accommodation is made to their known limitations.  If the   accommodation cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue   hardship, such persons may not be eligible.  CODES: M32-53545                     JMR                 7/30/93

