CHIEF BUREAU OF TRANSPORTATION SERVICES    DEFINITION:Under the direction of the Director or Deputy Director, Division of Purchase and Property,  Department of the Treasury, has responsibility for the management, administration and supervision  of the State's employee transportation services program, including automotive fleet management,  parking administration and travel administration; does related work as required. EXAMPLES OF WORKGuides and coordinates operating unit performance by means of a continuing review of unit  organization, policy, selected paperwork and work systems and by critical reviews and analyses of  monthly reports submitted by unit supervisors.Organizes the work of the Bureau of Transportation Services, prepares work programs and  develops work procedures,Sets standards for the preparation, receipt, review and processing of agency vehicular purchase or  assignment, parking space or permit assignment and travel accommodation requests.Sets and monitors standards for the timely, efficient repair, maintenance and fueling of fleet  vehicles.Develops and publishes uniform rules and regulations governing agency compliance with  prevailing vehicle use, parking and travel policies.Confers with agency representatives to define and develop plan for meeting automotive  transportation, parking and travel required to meet State program requirements.Supervises the conduct of extensive vehicle utilization audits to improve overall fleet vehicle  efficiency and to develop innovative programs to meet legitimate agency automotive transportation  needs.Directs the Central Motor Pool's automotive maintenance program, including development of a  quality control program and implementation of innovative vehicular repair methods and procedures.Supervises the administration and allocation of State-owned and leased parking facilities.Directs the annual replacement of fleet automobiles and the purchase of new vehicles to meet  expanded agency transportation needs.Supervises the receipt, investigation and resolution of citizen complaints against State vehicle  drivers and the preparation of fully documented complaint cases for presentation to Cabinet  officials.Assists the Purchase Bureau Supervisor in the development and preparation of performance-  oriented automotive and travel specifications.Directs the identification and transport to public auction of surplus fleet vehicles and automotive  parts.Prepares and directs the preparation of financial, statistical and other reports containing findings,  conclusions and recommendations.Directs the development, installation and continuous operation of a vehicular management  information system.Directs the purchase, storage and disbursement of automotive parts, supplies, equipment and fuel.Prepares complex correspondence in the course of official duties.Develops and implements policy governing the purchase, assignment, operation and maintenance  of Central Motor Pool vehicles; the allocation and utilization of State-owned or leased parking  facilities; and the planning, procurement and monitoring of State employee travel, by receiving,  setting and implementing objectives and considering timetables, cost efficiencies, contingencies,  available resources, technical research and computer data.Provides information to the State Treasurer, the Division Director and Deputy Director to assist  them in planning and the decision-making as it relates to automotive fleet management, employee  parking administration and employee travel services.Designs and adjusts the Bureau structure, usually by function or project, to provide a strategic  arrangement for the attainment of Bureau objectives including the preparation and dissemination of  charts, manuals, job specifications, procedures and budget information.Establishes lines of authority and communication throughout the major key result areas including  the office of the Bureau chief, the Central Motor Pool, Fleet Management Section, Parking   Administration section and Travel Services Section.Makes timely decisions to ensure compliance with organization objectives and policies by  integration of thought, attention to details, priority ordering, and the consideration of operations  research, information systems, cost factors, resources and a logical decision-making process.Directs the preparation, presentation and administration of the annual, Bureau and Travel Services  budgets.Represents the Bureau or a superior to accomplish organizational objectives in the area of public  relations, i.e., influencing the environment external to the organization or in specific occurrences,  such as meetings, conferences or public inquiries by utilizing a knowledge of organizational policy  and communication techniques.Negotiates with an individual or individuals to resolve disagreement whenever lines of authority do  not effectively extend.Supervises the work operations and/or functional programs and has responsibility for effectively  recommending the hiring, firing, promoting, demoting and/or disciplining of employees.Directs or participates in the preparation of complex and detailed analyses.Directs the establishment and maintenance of essential records and files.May be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual recording and  information systems used by the agency, office or related units. REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Ten (10) years of professional experience in a large central service agency, i.e., an agency responsible for such services as determining and implementing need assessment and provision for automotive support, employee parking and travel services, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and six (6) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a Master's degree from an accredited college or university in Public Administration, Business Administration, Finance, or Management; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIESAbility to acquire thorough knowledge of all the principals involved in coordinating the assignment,  use, storage, maintenance, repair, identification and purchase of motor vehicles and related  equipment for all State departments.Ability to acquire thorough knowledge of the State's departments' programs requiring the use of  State-owned or leased motor vehicles, parking facilities or private travel accommodations.Wide knowledge of modern supervisory practices and techniques.Ability to acquire thorough knowledge of the State budgeting and accounting/purchasing process  and relevant fiscal responsibilities.Ability to acquire considerable knowledge of State vehicle assignment and use policies, rules and  regulations; State travel regulations; federal and commercial air and hotel rules, regulations and  practices; and State Police parking laws, rules and regulations.Ability to acquire considerable knowledge of public personnel administration, Civil Service rules  and regulations, and internal Division and Departmental policies as they relate to employees and  staffing of the organization.Considerable knowledge of new and used car markets, fuel efficiency, safety and maintenance  records, and unusual departmental needs, to determine the what, when and where in the purchase,  assignment, use or disposal of State vehicles.Considerable knowledge of modern fleet management data processing information systems.Considerable knowledge of effective data presentation and report writing techniques.Ability to apply planning techniques to effectively develop unit policy and design/alter organizational  structure.Ability to design and utilize control mechanisms, such as performance indices, internal audits and  accounting data, for the purpose of maintaining a planned level of efficiency in Bureau operations.Ability to supervise, assign and evaluate the work of subordinate employees.Ability to apply leadership/motivation principles that will enable employees to attain organizational  goals.Ability to act as a representative of the Bureau or a superior. Ability to utilize accepted management practices and techniques.Ability to direct the preparation of and to administer a multi-million dollar operating budgetAbility to interpret operations research data, basic accounting information, computer information  and reports of varying complexity.Ability to analyze and interpret basic laws and vehicle use, parking, travel, accounting and  purchasing regulations as they relate to work programs, schedules, vehicle requirements and State  department or agency needs.Ability to make studies, surveys and investigations as a part of planning and decision-making, and  to prepare reports that clearly present findings, conclusions and recommendations.Ability to identify management information needs and oversee the development and operation of a  computerized management information reporting system.Ability to prepare extensive correspondence in the course of official duties.Ability to direct the maintenance of essential records and files.Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual recording and information  systems used by the agency, office or related units.Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in English sufficiently to perform the  duties of this position. American Sign Language or braille may also be considered as acceptable  forms of communication.Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long as they can perform the essential  functions of the job after reasonable accommodation is made to their known limitations. If the  accommodation cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue hardship, such  persons may not be eligible. This job specification is applicable to the following title code:JobSpecCodeVariantState,Local orCommonClass ofServiceWorkWeekStateClassCodeLocalClassCodeSalaryRangeNote52620SCNL

