DISPUTE RESOLUTION SPECIALIST 1    DEFINITION:          Under close supervision of a higher level supervisory official    in a state department, acts as an arbitrator, case evaluator,    conciliator, facilitator, fact-finder, mediator, or negotiator and is    responsible for designing and developing processes and systems for    particular contexts or types of disputes. Designs and administers    training programs; assesses situations for appropriate alternative    dispute resolution (ADR) intervention; develops, implements, and    monitors dispute resolution programs; and promotes and encourages    dispute resolution processes. Determines the most appropriate dispute    resolution process for disputes referred from the courts or other    government/public agencies. Conducts facilitations regarding the    development of new rules and policies through consensus building;    does related work as required.   NOTE: The definition and examples of work for this title are for    illustrative purposes only. A particular position using this title    may not perform all duties listed in this job specification.    Conversely, all duties performed on the job may not be listed.   NOTE: The following are some of the factors that should be considered    in determining case complexity: relationship between the parties, the    number of parties and issues in dispute, whether personal emotions    are involved, and the age of the dispute.  EXAMPLES OF WORK:    Determines the most appropriate dispute resolution process for    disputes referred from the courts.         Conducts facilitations regarding the development of new rules    and policies through consensus building.         Determines and directs when sessions should be arranged between    the principals in dispute and utilizes skills to resolve the    differences.         Persuades parties as to the reasonableness and equity of    proposals and counter-proposals as well as suggesting alternative    solutions.         Confers with disputants separately and jointly to assess    information pertaining to the issues in dispute and provides    assistance and pertinent data to remove barriers to resolution.          Trains public agency personnel, attorneys, and other relevant    parties in negotiation and dispute resolution techniques.          Designs case specific alternative dispute resolution    processes.        Develops case specific protocol.         Directs settlement discussions by identifying parties,    developing mechanisms for reporting back to constituents, scheduling    meetings, and setting agenda.          Assists parties in identifying policy issues through    facilitating effective exchange of information.        Assists parties in defining suitable negotiation goals.           Prepares analytic guidance documents that frame    policy/procedural issues for discussion and decision making.         Meets with disputing parties separately to explore possible    solutions, defuse emotions, and clarify positions.        Suggests possible approaches to settlement.        Drafts settlement agreement or final recommendation report.         Designs training programs in negotiation, mediation, and other    alternative dispute resolution processes.         Trains groups in the use of dispute resolution methods and    techniques.         Conducts educational and outreach activities to inform the    public, community groups, professional associations, and government    agencies about the dispute resolution process.         Oversees the development of written reports and final    settlement or recommendation documents prepared by the designated    individual, and modifies as appropriate and gives final approval    prior to release and dissemination of such documents.         Summarizes information from files, reports, documents, research    notes, or meetings.        Edits written material.        Interviews individuals for needed information.         Will be required to learn to utilize various types of    electronic and/or manual recording and computerized information    systems used by the agency, office, or related units.    REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Six (6) years of professional experience in mediating litigation and public disputes and/or facilitating the development of new rules or policies through consensus building.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and two (2) years of the above-mentioned professional experience.ORPossession of a Master's degree from an accredited college or university in Dispute/Conflict Resolution; and one (1) year of the above-mentioned professional experience.ORPossession of a Juris Doctor's degree.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:              Knowledge of the legal and factual issues involved in the    resolution of litigation and public disputes.              Knowledge of current alternative dispute resolution    processes, principles, and methods.              Knowledge of procedures for conducting formal and informal    hearings and conferences.              Ability to organize and interpret data and draw reasonable    and accurate conclusions.              Ability to assess noncomplex cases to determine the    appropriate application of the dispute resolution process.              Ability to plan, schedule, and conduct joint meetings    between disputing parties.              Ability to deal effectively with disputants and other    interested parties.              Ability to conduct around-the-clock dispute resolution    sessions.             Ability to interview people for needed information.             Ability to impartially communicate a thorough, complete    analysis of the position and flexibility of each disputant involved    to the other disputant(s).             Ability to organize assigned dispute resolution work.              Ability to analyze dispute resolution problems and develop    effective work methods.               Ability to maintain confidentiality in dispute resolution    proceedings.             Ability to conduct training sessions.             Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic    and/or manual recording and information systems used by the agency,    office, or related units.               Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate    in English sufficiently to perform the duties of this position.    American Sign Language or Braille may also be considered as    acceptable forms of communication.              Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible    as long as they can perform the essential functions of the job after    reasonable accommodation is made to their known limitations. If the    accommodation cannot be made because it would cause the employer    undue hardship, such persons may not be eligible.   CODES: 27/P27-21816 CAH 6/22/96

