MANAGEMENT INFORMATION SYSTEMS COORDINATOR    DEFINITION: Under the general supervision of a supervisory official in a state or  local department, institution or agency, coordinates department or  agency data processing, word processing, and data communications  activities to ensure efficient and effective installation and use,  directs all data processing projects and assigned staff; leads the  need analysis, operations analysis, and systems analysis activities  for the operation, implementation, and enhancement of all agency data  processing, word processing, and data communications facilities, and  resources; does other related duties. NOTE: The examples of work for this title are for illustrative  purposes only. A particular position using this title may not perform  all duties listed in this job specification. Conversely, all duties  performed on the job may not be listed.     EXAMPLES OF WORK: Supervises the installation, operation, maintenance, and assignment   of all department or agency data processing facilities and resources;  plans and/or supervises the planning for expansion of all data  processing services. Establishes and implements policies for efficient and cost- effective  management information systems. Coordinates all department or agency data processing plans with the  State-level Office of Telecommunications and Information Systems or  other appropriate authority ensuring that all data processing systems  are fully compatible and consistent with strategic guidelines for  information processing, including architecture and networking  capabilities. Plans, organizes, and directs studies of existing and planned data  processing applications to determine the capacity, utilization,  potential uses, and need for existing and/or proposed equipment. Plans for the purchase of the hardware and software necessary to  satisfy department or agency data processing requirements, including  processors, data communications equipment, data base management  systems, and various applications technology. Develops and supervises the development of data processing/data  communications plans, including a specific specification development  process, requests for proposal development, responses to bidders  inquiries and proposal evaluations, and the recommendation of  appropriate courses of action. Provides both short and long range budgetary forecasts on department  or agency data processing approaches and on an annual basis analyzes  data processing/word processing and data communications requirements,  and provides recommendations for fiscal year planning and budget  submissions. Supervises feasibility studies; reviews detailed analysis of functions  to determine the advisability of adopting a data processing approach;  selects courses of action for applications from recommendations and  cost estimates. Evaluates requests and recommends appropriate action on those requests  for computer hardware, software, systems, personnel services, support  services, and other items of a data processing nature. Supervises the preparation of schedules and outlines the essential  steps to be taken in the installation and/or conversion to data  processing systems. As may be required, supervises the project work assignments and work  operations of assigned staff and has responsibility for effectively  recommending appropriate personnel and project action. Prepares and supervises the preparation of charts, programs, and  instructions as needed to illustrate, explain, and implement data  processing procedures and programs; studies procedural difficulties  and operating problems and recommends measures to be taken in their  solution. Supervises the development of standards and procedures for usage of  all department or agency data processing/word processing systems. Supervises department or agency systems analysis, design, and related  matters and acts as advisor to management in matters involving data  processing equipment and staff. Acts as an internal consultant and advisor to the department or agency  in matters involving data processing and word processing equipment,  staff, approaches to using computer technology, budgets, and  expenditures. Initiates and coordinates all department or agency plans for data  processing, word processing, and data communications services. Orients and outlines training requirements to staff and/or training  consultants for the department or agency regarding management  information systems. Prepares and supervises the preparation of reports of data processing  matters containing findings, conclusions, and recommendations. Finalizes and presents project plans for administrative decisions. Manages the work operations and/or functional programs and has  responsibility for employee evaluations and for effectively  recommending the hiring, firing, promoting, demoting, and/or  disciplining of employees. Maintains, develops, and assigns projects to various unit members. Directs staff on on-going projects and assignments. Supervises the investigation and solution of real or potential problem  areas. Participates in conferences. Supervises the establishment and maintenance of essential records,  reports and files. Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic  and/or manual recording and information systems used by the agency,  office, or related units.  REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Nine (9) years of professional experience in the analysis and development of management information systems, two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity with responsibility for the coordination and/or planning, and/or implementation of data processing systems.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity with responsibility for the coordination and/or planning, and/or implementation of data processing systems.ORPossession of a Master's degree from an accredited college or university in business, finance, accounting, public administration, or data processing; and four (4) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity with responsibility for the coordination and/or planning, and/or implementation of data processing systems.  NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES: Knowledge of data processing, management theory, principals, and  techniques, including organizational structure, staffing requirements,  and administrative controls. Knowledge of electronic data processing and data communications  equipment, and their selection and applicability to the specific  applications. Knowledge of the broad spectrum of data processing technologies  including mainframe, mini, and microcomputer hardware, operating  systems, and software. Knowledge of broad spectrum of data communications technologies  including mainframe teleprocessing and distributed processing system  concepts, office automation networking, large scale local area  networking, microcomputer local, area networking, and private branch  exchange networks for integrated voice and data communications. Knowledge of word processing hardware and software and methods for  utilizing this tool in the most efficient and cost effective manner,  including other forms of office automation. Knowledge of microcomputer systems, peripheral devices and supportive  operational equipment, and their potential limitations in specific  application areas. Knowledge of techniques used to conduct surveys, feasibility studies,  operational analyses, and systems studies regarding development plans,  budgeting, operations implementation and other specialized planning  and research methods. Knowledge of the various project scheduling techniques including but  not limited to Critical Path Management (CPM), PERT, and GANTT. Knowledge of the factors to be considered in gauging the effect of  change or additions to data processing environment. Ability to interpret and apply information on policies, procedures,  regulations, and functions of the department or agency. Ability to interpret and apply information on the state budget process  and procurement procedures, purchasing statutes and the components of  hardware and software specificity to ensure appropriate approvals for  agency data processing purchases. Ability to plan, comprehend, analyze and implement data processing  methods in the engineering, statistical, administrative, and financial  areas of the department or agency. Ability to develop, organize, and manage significant technical data  processing projects. Ability to prepare schedules for the installation of data processing  methods and to assign personnel that ensure that these schedules are  met. Ability to prepare charts, programs, and instructions, and to  illustrate, explain, and implement data processing procedures and  programs. Ability to develop and coordinate training programs. Ability to give appropriate assignments and instructions to analysts  and development staff and clerical employees and supervise the  performance of their work. Ability to direct other consultants and technical specialists in  performing assigned project tasks. Ability to act as consultant and advisor on data processing matters to  various Divisions, Offices, and Bureaus within the department or  agency. Ability to oversee applications areas, intra-agency relations, and  solutions of users' problems. Ability to analyze existing data processing problems and recommend  solutions. Ability to communicate effectively with technical staff and agency  heads. Ability to prepare correspondence. Ability to prepare and supervise the preparation of reports, and plans  containing findings, conclusions, and recommendations. Ability to supervise the maintenance of the essential records reports,  and files. Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and information systems used by the agency, office, or  related units. Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in English  sufficiently to perform the duties of this position. American Sign  Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of  communication. Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long as  they can perform the essential functions of the job after reasonable  accommodation is made to their known limitations. If the accommodation  cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue hardship,  such persons may not be eligible.   This job specification is applicable to the following title code:JobSpecCodeVariantState,Local orCommonClass ofServiceWorkWeekStateClassCode

