GOVERNMENTAL RELATIONS SPECIALIST 1    DEFINITION:        Under general direction of a supervisory official in a state   department, institution, or agency, conducts research and analyzes   policy issues for the Commissioner, and/or supervises a staff engaged   in the preparation of correspondence for the Governor and/or   Commissioner, and the preparation of material concerning department   programs for publication; does related work as required.  EXAMPLES OF WORK:        Investigates special public policy problem areas, and develops   recommendations, as requested by the Commissioner and other department   management.       Monitors current and pending regulations for impact on consumers,   paying special attention to the plain language mandates of the   legislature and department.       Represents the Commissioner at department boards, public meetings,   and seminars.       Plans, organizes, and assigns the work of the organizational unit   and evaluates employee performance and conduct, enabling the effective   recommendation of the hiring, firing, promoting, and disciplining of   subordinates.       Serves as coordinator and Commissioner's representative on special   task forces.       Writes and presents speeches to general audiences concerning the   department's views and policies, and coordinates speaking engagements.       Plans and implements operation systems including computerized   recordkeeping and data retrieval system for essential records and   files.       Analyzes, interprets, and answers complex correspondence referred   by the Governor's Office and legislators in reference to inquiries   concerning controversial subjects and consumer complaints.       Develops and prepares correspondence for the signature of the   Governor, Commissioner, and other department management.       Acts as technical adviser with other departments on policy issues.       Followsup on the status of pending investigations relating to   complaints.       Analyzes, interprets, and prepares technical reports and   newsletters on policy issues for the various divisions within the   department, other state and federal agencies, or county and municipal   governments.       Meets with the public and others to discuss current policy issues   and to offer suggestions for problems that may arise.       Interacts with other state and federal agencies, or county and   municipal governments concerning the department's functions, aims,   programs, regulations, policies, and procedures.       Researches, compiles, prepares, formats, and distributes   newsletters, news releases, speeches, bulletins, pamphlets and other   information material designed to acquaint the general public with   functions, goals, programs, regulations, policies, and procedures of   the department.       Meets and confers with other department staff with respect to   research and inquiries concerning the application of the department's   regulations and statutes.       Attends meetings, conferences, committee hearings, and other group   meetings pertinent to the work of the department and records thereon.       Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic   and/or manual recording and computerized information system used by the   agency, office, or related units. REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education.  Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.Seven (7) years of professional experience in written and verbal communication.  Such experience may include, but is not limited to the following:  interpreting technical material and/or rules, regulations, and statutes for the public working in an area concerned with consumer services, journalism, communication education, public affairs.ORPossession of a Bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and three (3) years of the above-mentioned professional experience.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgement and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointee will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:       Knowledge of state and federal laws, rules, regulations, and   policies affecting the programs and activities of the department after   a period of training.       Knowledge of the procedures involved in collecting, analyzing,   investigating, and interpreting data, often complex in nature, and the   presentation of such information after a period of training.       Knowledge of the basic principles and materials used in journalism   and public relations after a period of training.       Knowledge of the problems encountered in using factual data from   various sources, drawing reasonable and correct conclusions, and   making use of facts pertinent to specific cases in clear, concise, and   public information form for bulletins, pamphlets, and speeches after a   period of training.       Knowledge of agency programs, policies, objectives, and reports   thereon after a period of training.       Ability to write and deliver speeches on current issues and   policies of the department.       Ability to analyze and interpret basic law and regulations and to   collect, analyze, and interpret technical and other factual data.       Ability to prepare and direct the staff in the preparation of   clear, technically sound, accurate, information and statistical reports   containing findings, conclusions, and recommendations.       Ability to maintain essential records and files.       Ability to maintain liason with the public and other state and   federal agencies.       Ability to organize complex assignments and develop work methods.       Ability to prepare, review, and edit written material and to proof   read copy.       Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or   manual recording and information systems used by the agency, office, or   related units.       Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in   English sufficiently to perform the duties of this position.  American   Sign Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of   communication.       Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long   as they can perform the essential functions of the job after reasonable   accommodation is made to their known limitations.  If the accommodation   persons may not be eligible.  CODES:  R26-54444                     ECK                3/20/95

