CHIEF CONTRACT ADMINISTRATION SECTION    DEFINITION: Under general direction of a supervisory official, develops policy and  guidelines for the implementation and administration of services  through contractual arrangements or, oversees the administration of  statewide construction and/or professional services contracts; does  other related work. NOTE: The examples of work for this title are for illustrative  purposes only. A particular position using this title may not perform  all duties listed in this job specification. Conversely, all duties  performed on the job may not be listed.  EXAMPLES OF WORK: Plans, organizes and assigns the work of the organizational unit and  evaluates employee performance and conduct enabling the effective  recommendation of the hiring, firing, promoting, and disciplining of  subordinates. Directs the development and administration of contracts for the  provision of services; conducts the solicitation or Request for  Purchase (RFP) bidding process, negotiates and drafts contract  language, develops evaluation criteria, awards or coordinates the  review and selection process for the awarding of contracts, monitors  contractees for compliance with contract requirements, conducts  on-site audits, evaluates effectiveness of contracted services and  provision of consultation and expertise to Using Agency management. Exercises review and approval authority over all phases of the  contract process for the provision of services at all levels of the  department, from proposal preparation through contract monitoring,  reporting, modification, evaluation, audit compliance, and contract  closeout. Directs the development of standardized systems for the preparation,  reviewing, processing, and recording of vouchers, change orders,  progress reports, financial statements, proposal forms and contract  documents. Directs fiscal administration aspects of contracts/grants, including  procurement, vendor invoice review and processing, financial analysis,  quality assurance, change orders and resolution of disputes and  appeals. Acts as liaison between the using agencies, the Department and outside  architects and contractors on matters relating to the transmittal of  tracings, blueprints, available funds, and reports during the  development of projects. Directs the development of procedure manuals and policy transmittals  containing financial, programmatic, and administrative contracting  guidelines. Attends conferences and meetings with architects, engineers,  construction contractors and others to outline State procedures and  requirements. Oversees contract/grant closeout activities, including final invoice  payments, compliance inspections and audits. Designs, plans, and directs budget activities, including budget  preparation, fiscal reports, budget interpretation, and provides  fiscal advice to the Director. Provides advise and assistance to the department operating officials  in matters of contract administration. Participates in the development and implementation of a computerized  contract information system and manages its ongoing utilization  including the development and direction of in-service programs. Directs the provision of technical assistance in the areas of  proposal/contract/preparation, review and approval, development and  management of adequate contract/grant administration and financial  reporting systems, contract/grant monitoring, amendment and closeout,  audit compliance and service evaluation. Develops and implements a system of monitoring division contracting  systems to ensure they meet minimum department standards. Provides technical assistance to personnel of user agencies regarding  the development and management of contract administration and  reporting systems. Identifies and studies problems in the area of contract  administration, recommends solutions and participates in the  resolution of audit findings. Analyzes the impact of new legislation and regulations on the contract  operations of the department and makes changes in procedures as  appropriate. Serves as department liaison with federal, local, and other state  government agencies. Prepares analytical reports. Compiles and reports data to other operational units. Supervises the maintenance of records and files. Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic  and/or manual recording and computerized information system used by  the agency, office, or related units.  REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.Nine (9) years of professional experience in work involving contract administration, program administration, financial management, and analysis, and/or budgets and management operations of a government or business entity, at least three (3) years of which shall have been in contract administration in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, at least three (3) years of which shall have been in contract administration in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a master's degree in Business Administration or Public Administration; and four (4) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, at least three (3) years of which shall have been in contract administration in a supervisory capacity.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the  position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES: Knowledge of supervisory techniques. Knowledge of financial accounting principles and records, principles  of cost allowability and reasonableness, contract budget principles,  matching fund accounting, and procurement guidelines. Knowledge of the legal and administrative requirements concerning  contractual agreements. Ability to supervise a staff of professional and clerical employees  and to conduct the day-to-day operation of the section. Ability to define objectives and to determine costs of operating the  section. Ability to recognize problems and to prepare and present department  management analytical reports containing problem statements, data  analyses, conclusions, and recommendations. Ability to understand, interpret, and apply federal and state laws  pertinent to the contract operations of a state agency and communicate  this understanding and interpretation in the form of clear and concise  guidelines and directives. Ability to interpret the intent and impact of legislation, guidelines,  rules, and regulations on the contracting policies and procedures of  the department. Ability to interpret technical data and procedures in response to  questions from provider organization employees and appropriate  division and department personnel. Ability to make effective use of available training modes and methods. Ability to prepare analytical reports, containing data analyses,  conclusions, and recommendations. Ability to supervise the maintenance of records and files. Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and information systems used by the agency, office, or  related units. Ability to read, write, speak, understand or communicate in English  sufficiently to perform the duties of this position. American Sign  Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of  communication. Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long as  they can perform the essential functions of the job after reasonable  accommodation is made to their known limitations. If the accommodation  cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue hardship,  such persons may not be eligible.This job specification is applicable to the following title code:JobSpecCodeVariantState,Local orCommonClass ofServiceWorkWeekStateClassCodeLocalClassCodeSalaryRangeNote61679SCNL32N/A&32-This job specification is for state government use only.Salary range is only applicable to state government.Local salaries are established by individual local jurisdictions. 6/4/2004

