SUPERVISOR REGIONAL FOOD SERVICE OPERATION    DEFINITION:        Under direction of a supervisory official in the Department of   Corrections, or Department of Human Services, is responsible for the   storage, preparation, delivery, and service of all food for several   large institutions within a designated region; does related work as   required.  EXAMPLES OF WORK:        Plans the work program and working procedures and, when these have   been approved, develops appropriate schedules and methods.       Assigns and instructs employees and inmates in the food service   units and supervises work performance.       Makes and executes plans for the effective utilization of   available funds, personnel, equipment, materials,and supplies.       Prepares recommendations concerning and coordinates planning of   the vegetable, fruit, dairy, and meat production programs of the   various institutions and evaluating the required personnel, funds,   materials, equipment and supplies.       Supervises the preparation of requisitions for all food supplies   and food preparation, equipment, and materials, to be acquired by   direct purchase, and sees that these are properly stored, safeguarded,   recorded, and utilized.       Ensures proper health, sanitary, and safety conditions and   standards; inspects all areas where food supplies are received,   handled, stored, refrigerated, prepared,and served.       Supervises, coordinates, and reviews the preparation of all menus,   special diets, and therapeutic diets; ensures that proper food supplies   are available to implement such diets; ensures that the recommendation   of the medical and dietetic staff are carried out.       Ensures that meals are properly prepared utilizing both   conventional and regithermic methods; ensures that all meals are   delivered according to an established schedule.       Prepares factual records and makes recommendation concerning the   "re-thermalizing" and serving of food by the receiving kitchens.       Prepares reports and maintains and supervises the maintenance of   files and records.       Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic   and/or manual recording and information systems used by the agency,   office, or related units.   REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.  Eight (8) years of professional experience in the management of a complex institution or commercial unit; two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and four (4) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a master's degree in Home Economics, Dietetics, Food Management, or associated field; and three (3) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, two (2) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:   Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:           Knowledge of modern dietetics, institutional diet management,   and commercial or hotel institutional food preparation and service,   including food costs estimating and accounting.           Knowledge of the principle and procedure involved in   regithermic cooking.           Knowledge of health, sanitary, and safety standards for   kitchen personnel, equipment, appliances, and routines.           Ability to plan, organize, and implement commercial or   institutional food service operation, using skilled, unskilled,   patient, student, and/or inmate labor, and to utilize effectively the   products of the institution farm, dairy, and butcher shop where these   are available, making use of seasonal products and institution crops.           Ability to determine/evaluate the quality of varied types of   food and food supplies.           Ability to develop nutritional and economical menus for a   large number of persons.           Ability to comprehend budget preparation.           Ability to give instructions to staff and supervise work   performance.           Ability to see that food preparation service and storage areas   are maintained in a clean, orderly, and safe condition at all times.           Ability to prepare correspondence and reports and supervise   the maintenance of files.           Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or   manual recording and information systems used by the agency, office, or   related units.           Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in   English sufficiently to perform the duties of this position.  American   Sign Language or Braille may also be considered as acceptable forms of   communication.           Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as   long as they can perform the essential functions of the job after   reasonable accommodation is made to their known limitations.  If the   accommodation cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue   hardship, such persons may not be eligible.  CODES: 27/S28-44729               LJG                     05/11/95

