CONFEREE 1 TAXATION    DEFINITION: Under direction of a Conferee 2, Taxation or other supervisory  official in Division of Taxation, Department of the Treasury,  conducts administrative conferences entailing  substantive    tax issues of importance and difficulty involving taxpayer' protests  of tax determinations made on behalf of the Director, Division of  Taxation; under direction, prepares reports and determination  recommendations on protested tax matters; does related duties   as required. NOTE: The  examples of work for this title are for illustrative  purposes only.  A particular positionusing this title may not  perform all duties listed in this job specification. Conversely,  all duties performed on the job may not be listed.  EXAMPLES OF WORK: Conducts conferences in less complicated cases of disputed   legal and/or factual issues resulting from a determination of   the Division Director. Assists Conferee 2 in conduct of conferences in complicated   cases of disputed legal and/or factual issues resulting from  a determination of the Division Director. Conducts  conferences  in less complicated cases  with  taxpayers  and/or  their  representatives to discuss  proposed  assessments,  review  differences,  and report on reasons  for  differences  of  opinions. Assists Conferee 2 in conduct of conferences in complicated cases  with  taxpayers and/or their representatives to discuss  proposed  assessments,  review  differences,  and  report  on  reasons  for  differences of opinions. Prepares a comprehensive conference report using work papers,  other underlying documentation, and opinions of the auditor, tax  services   specialist,  deputy  attorney  general,  and   others;  develops case for determination. Reviews contested cases to determine whether accounting  verification methods and procedures used in initial determination  were in accordance with laws and regulations; makes comments    and recommendations as appropriate. Reviews, interprets and applies points of law, applicable  regulations, court cases and division policy to tax issues    under consideration. Consults with higher authority to request opinions on complicated  determination matters. Interprets tax statutes and regulations to taxpayers and/or their  representative. Prepares correspondence regarding final determination on  contested matters for the Conferee 2 or other supervisory staff. Reviews request for conferences as needed. Requests necessary information from taxpayer or taxpayer's  representatives to objectively render a decision on facts as  presented by both division and taxpayer. Corresponds with taxpayers and/or their representatives regarding  protest on tax matters. As required,  assists tax services specialists and/or deputy  attorney generals in preparation of cases before judiciary. Keeps current with legislative changes in New Jersey Tax  Statutes, Internal Revenue Code, and court decisions that    affect Division of Taxation. Provides  general information regarding conferences, tax appeals,  application  of tax laws, and auditing techniques,  for  division  personnel, legal and accounting communities, and general public. Appears as witness for division in court proceedings as required. Maintains records and files. Will be required to utilize various types of electronic and/or  manual recording and computerized information systems   used by the agency, office, or related units.  REQUIREMENTS: NOTE:Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester-hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.Seven (7) years of professional experience in accounting or auditing, one (1) year which shall have involved the conduct of conferences of protested determinations of financial liability on behalf of a governmental entity, or the examination and verification of internal and taxpayer accounts and records to determine financial obligations, including or supplemented by twenty-one (21) semester-hour credits in accounting courses.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university, including or supplemented by twenty-one (21) semester-hour credits in accounting courses; and three (3) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, one (1) year of which shall have involved the conduct of conferences of protested determinations of financial liability on behalf of a governmental entity, or the examination and verification of internal and taxpayer accounts and records to determine financial obligations.ï¿½NOTE:"Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointee will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES: Knowledge of common types of violations and evasion of State  Tax regulations after a period of training. Knowledge of modern accounting, auditing, and/or examination    and verification methods as applied to examination and review   of tax returns and books of account. Knowledge of  location, proper form, content, and interpretation  of legal and varied types of  financial records/documents,  statements,  audits, instruments, and other documents  and    their use. Knowledge of Internal Revenue Code and its application to    New Jersey Tax Acts. Knowledge of reciprocal agreement between State and  Internal Revenue Service after a period of training. Ability to comprehend and apply provisions of New Jersey  tax statutes administered by division and division regulations,  policies, standards, and procedures. Ability to research tax issues via printed and/or electronic tax  information services. Ability to conform to provisions of the New Jersey Confidentiality    Act, New Jersey Taxpayer  Bill  of  Rights,  and Federal Privacy   Act of 1974. Ability  to  organize and implement hearing procedures  regarding  less complicated tax audits. Ability to organize assigned tax work and develop effective  work  methods. Ability  to  execute orders and directions as required  by  court  decisions or rulings and/or promulgated by Director. Ability to explain and interpret tax laws in a lucid, convincing,  concise manner to taxpayers, business, financial, accounting,   and legal experts. Ability  to  interpret  and apply available guidelines,  evaluate  factual  situations,  weigh  merits of  evidence,  arguments  and  briefs,  and  anticipate  and  meet  possible  attacks  on  State  position. Ability to confer with business and trade representatives,  attorneys, corporate officials, and other persons concerning    tax problems. Ability to maintain State position and policy regarding tax  matters. Ability to compose detailed, technical correspondence relating   to taxes administered by the division. Ability to facilitate a harmonious conference atmosphere. Ability to listen and comprehend a taxpayer's contentions with  respect to matters under review. Ability to work cooperatively with associates and  subordinates  and with those interested in or concerned with the immediate   case at hand. Ability to learn to confer with legal representatives of taxpayers    and understand mechanics of mergers, conglomerates,  absorptions, and other actions concerning reorganization of  business entities. Ability to present evidence for State in court proceedings on tax  matters. Ability to clearly and cogently explain taxpayer's rights  regarding audit and/or investigation of  their records and   conference and appeal process as required by Taxpayer's    Bill of Rights, and division collection process. Ability  to  use  a  personal  computer,  including  spreadsheet,  database, and word-processing applications. Ability  to  use  division  computer main-frame  and  information  systems. Ability to explore and resolve apparent alternate arguments  that  would   typically   be  raised  if  taxpayer   had   professional  representation. Ability  to  learn to utilize various types of electronic  and/or  manual  recording  and information systems used  by  the    agency, office, or related units. Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in  English  sufficiently  to perform the duties  of  this  position.  American Sign Language or Braille may also be considered    as acceptable forms of communication. Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long  as they can perform essential functions of the job with or without   reasonable accommodation.  If the accommodation cannot be made  because it would cause the employer undue hardship, such persons   may not be eligible.This job specification is applicable to the following title code:JobSpecCodeVariantState,Local orCommonClass ofServiceWorkWeekStateClassCodeLocalClassCodeSalaryRangeNote51318SCNL26N/AP26-This job specification is for state government use only.Salary range is only applicable to state government.Local salaries are established by individual local jurisdictions. 9/15/2018

