REALTY SPECIALIST 4 TRANSPORTATION    DEFINITION:Under the supervision of a Right of Way District Program Manager or other  Manager, supervises staff in the administrative and operational ROW program  areas associated with property acquisition and disposition; Supervises  assignments on administrative or operational programs pertaining to the  Division of Right of Way & Access Management in areas such as negotiations,  relocation, property management, programming, administration and the laws  and principles of Eminent Domain; does other related duties as assigned.NOTE:  The examples of work for this title are for illustrative purposes only.  A particular position using this title may not perform all duties listed in this  job specification. Conversely, all duties performed on the job may not be listed. EXAMPLES OF WORK:Directly supervises assigned bureau personnel in their work and their  maintenance of required reports and records to ensure that all matters  are conducted in accordance with division procedure and requirements.Supervises the entire Appraisal process for all projects assigned to the Team.   Ensures delivery of appraisals and timely review of all cases.  Negotiates fees  for Appraisals, Appraisal Reviews and Specialist Reports with all consultant  appraisal firms.Is responsible for assisting the District Program Manager in the supervision of  the processing of acquisition matters in the assigned areas.  Informs the District  Program Manager of the production status of cases in the assigned District Offices  and of adherence to scheduled project completion dates; maintains appropriate  controls in status records.As delegated by the bureau manager, coordinates matters of condemnation  between Right of Way personnel, the Title Officer for the delivery of title memoranda,  the Division of the Design Services for the delivery of condemnation complaint maps,  and the Deputy Attorney General's Office.Supervises the distribution of cases involving the assignment and processing of  cases involved in Commission Awards, Consent Awards, and Jury Awards to the  Closing Bureau for final payment.Plans, organizes, and directs the work of district level teams.  Is responsible  for planning and scheduling work in the team and for assignment of work to the  various staff assigned to the team.Supervises personnel in their work and their maintenance of reports and records  to ensure that all qualitative and quantitative requirements of the state are met as  concerns the district.Determines the type of appraisal required considering the impact of the acquisition  and any damages related to the taking.  Orders the proper number of appraisals  based on the estimated acquisition cost.  Ensures coordination between appraisers  in the case of multiple reports.Is responsible for coordinating operations and assembling information relating  to the offer of assistance and relocation payments to eligible displaced persons.Supervises and controls the operations involved in inventorying improvements  acquired on various rights of way, scheduling the vacation of these improvements,  and arranging for final disposition of such improvements.  Is responsible, under the  Relocation Advisory Assistance and Moving Reimbursements programs, for the  receipt of completed applications, and the review and approval of moving cost  estimates due property owners.Reviews and guides others in regard to the Office of Access Design determination  of Access.  Ensures that appraisals are ordered that are consistent with the Access  Code regulations and case law regarding compensability of Access impacts.Reviews and guides others regarding any environmental impact PAECE reports.   Ensures that all reports required are prepared and provided to the property owners  as required by statute.As required, coordinates all the activities of full service Right of Way consultant  firms assigned to the team.  Includes the monitoring of all activities of the consultant  as well as providing reports to management regarding cost, schedule and scope  issues of the project.Is responsible for reviewing and processing completed cases submitted by the  District Offices.  Supervises the preparation of Department Action slips and the  collation and orderly arrangement of various papers essential to each use.Conducts negotiations pursuant to the standards set forth in the Administrative/Legal  Settlement Authorization Schedule.  Responsible for negotiation of terms and conditions for acquisition, disposal,  and/or leasing of property.Supervises preparation of package to be submitted to various commissions,  boards, and committees of the state as required by law and the division.Orders and reviews title searches, appraisals, and property surveys.Supervises the distribution of information on public lands to individuals and  public and private agenciesSupervises the processing of requests for information or disposal of land  owned by the DOT.  Ensures all requests are responded to in writing.Prepares reports and correspondence relating to Relocation Advisory Services  and disposal of surplus land functions.Confers regularly with the bureau manager and other responsible Right of Way  personnel on schedules and procedural clarifications of property and relocation  functions.Supervises assigned personnel in their work and the maintenance of reports and  records to ensure that all qualitative and quantitative requirements of the state are met.Confers regularly with the various headquarters office staff, District Program Manager,  and with the Director of the Division.Prepares reports and correspondence relating to the various operations and  activities of the Team.Assumes final responsibility at the district level for all operations and activities and  for the review and approval of all matters and cases forwarded to the District Program  Manager for processing to the headquarters office and to the Director for Commission  Action.Establishes and maintains appropriate master reports and files of matters  assigned the designated District areas.  Drafts correspondence necessary  in the conduct of assigned matters.As delegated by the bureau manager, supervises the processing and distribution  of approved agreements as executed by the Director, Division of Right of Way  and Access Management. Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and computerized information systems used by the agency, office,  or related units. REQUIREMENTS:NOTE:Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.  Nine (9) years of professional experience in any phase of Right of Way work subject to the Federal Highway Funding Reimbursement Program (e.g. appraisal, negotiations, relocation, property management or programming and admistration), which shall have included two (2) years of full-time supervisory experience.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, which shall have included two (2) years of full-time supervisory experience.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:Knowledge of the Right of Way Acquisition Manual and CFR 49, Uniform  Relocation Act.  Negotiation techniques necessary to plan and coordinate  a Right of Way acquisitions of highway projects and field operations of the  Division of Right of Way & Access Management.  Knowledge of and familiarity with the basic legal terms and concepts prevailing  in real estate law, including the laws and principles of Eminent Domain, and their  application to the work of the bureau.Knowledge of the institution of condemnation proceedings as they relate to  bureau activities, i.e. bad title, approval of agreements, inability to locate  owner, authority to condemn, and appeals.Knowledge of the types of appraisal methods available and the basics behind  the preparation of such appraisals.Knowledge of basic engineering concepts including, but not limited to, turning  templates, slope ratios, daily volumes and other items required for the preparation  of engineering reports.Knowledge of the NJ Access Code and the Access Code process as  implemented by the State as well as the ordering of Access Impact Reports  and studies.Knowledge of the Consultant Selection process and the Task Orders and  Proposals prepared for the use of full service Right of Way consultants.Knowledge of and familiarity with the cooperating operations relating to the  offer of assistance and relocation payments to eligible persons, with the  operations involved in the determination of improvements on Right of Way  properties and buildings, the schedule of vacation of these improvements,  and negotiations for final disposition of improvements on a statewide basis.Knowledge of and familiarity with the Relocation Payment program for the  receipt of completed applications, review, and approval of moving cost  estimates due displaced property owners and tenants.Knowledge of and familiarity with the administrative and technical problems  which arise in large scale property appraisal and Right of Way negotiation work.Knowledge of and familiarity with the basic legal terms and concepts prevailing  in real estate law, including the laws of Eminent Domain, and their application to  the work of the district.Knowledge of the methods and procedures used in preparing preliminary  estimates of Right of Way costs.Knowledge of the procedures and techniques used in determining the  soundness of titles and the determination of the owners of real estate, and  knowledge of the procedures for the evaluation of current and prospective  market values of property and improvements located thereon.Knowledge of and familiarity with the procedures approved for the use in  Right of Way negotiations and the interpretation of agreements, easements,  and descriptions of property.Knowledge of appraisal procedures as required by Federal and State government.Ability to discuss the interaction and distinction between the Access Code and  the Acquisition of Right of Way.  Can describe the appeal process of the Access  process and the Office of Administrative Law process as it relates to Access.Ability to explain the basics behind the environmental report including the areas  of testing, some of the concepts of the environmental findings and the overall  remediation recommendation.Ability to read and interpret legal agreements and descriptions of property.Ability to read and interpret real estate contracts, agreements, and building  specifications.Ability to make and supervise continuing studies and analyses to determine  real property management requirements and the necessity of revisions in  administrative procedures and programs.Ability to research and apply legal and administrative requirements of  contractual agreements.Ability to interpret and apply laws, regulations, policies, and procedures  relating to the acquisition, use, and maintenance of leased and owned  property programs.Ability to compile data and statistics for inclusion in the annual budget, and to  compare budget requests and the annual report of the bureau.  Ability to prepare  and direct the preparation of statistical, financial, and other requests of sectional  activities containing findings, conclusions, and recommendations.Ability to establish and maintain cooperative work relationships with landowners  and their attorneys, the representatives of business and civic organizations, and  the general public interested in or concerned with Department of Transportation  Right of Way matters.Ability to visualize, analyze, and interpret the varied problems e

