DIRECTOR OF EMPLOYEE RELATIONS HUMAN SERVICES    DEFINITION:Under the general guidance of the Deputy Commissioner for  Operations, Department of Human Services, represents the  Department in employee relations matters, directs the  formalization, implementation and administration of  Department policies and programs in all matters of employee  relations, and directs the work programs and staff of the  Office of Employee Relations: does related work as required.NOTE:  The examples of work for this title are for  illustrative purposes only.  A particular position using  this title may not perform all duties listed in this job  specification.  Conversely, all duties performed on the job  may not be listed. EXAMPLES OF WORKRepresents the Commissioner in negotiations between the  State and the certified majority representative of  State wide negotiation units.Makes binding commitments on behalf of the Department on  matters being negotiated.As Head of the Department Negotiating Team, directs all  aspects of the Department's participation in the  negotiations for the State wide unit agreements and, as  necessary, delegates authority to team members.As Chairman of the Department Negotiations Committee, meets  with  Division Directors, or their designees, as a Committee  to evaluate the  operational impact of majority  representatives' contractual demands and/or  the State's  counter proposals, so as, to provide input by the committee  members in the process of preparing the Department's  position and responses  thereto.Directs the preparation and presentation of Department  proposals and counter proposals for State wide negotiation  unit agreements and contracts.Acts as the Department liaison with the Governor's Office of  Employee Relations on all matters pertaining to employee  relations.Directs the administration of State wide negotiation unit  agreements and contracts for the Department.Determines the Department's position on the intent and  meaning of provisions of State wide negotiation unit  agreements and contracts.Determines which Department or Department component  policies, practices, procedures, operations, and/or work  rules are subject to mandatory modification as the result of  the provisions of a State wide negotiations unit agreement  between the State and the certified majority representative.Determines and directs the application of methods, practices  and technics, which will result in the successful  modification of the affected policies, practices,  procedures, operations and/or work rules.Provides consultative advice, support and input to the  Commissioner on all matters pertaining to employee relations  and negotiations.Consults with the Deputy Commissioner for Operations or the  Commissioner on situations which involve significant new or  very complex employee relations problems and recommends  methods by which to resolve  them.Organizes assigned administrative and technical work,  analyzes employee relations and personnel problems, and  develops appropriate work procedures for the Central Office  and other staff.Directs the implementation of employee relations programs,  policies, practices on procedures through the institution  and agency Employee Relations Officers and the staff of the  Office of Employee Relations.Establishes the need for and develops appropriate employee  relations policies and practices for the entire Department.Directs the continuous review and evaluation of employee  relations programs.Directs and maintains the Department level grievance  processing.Meets with majority representatives as required.Represents the Department in attempts to settle discipline  and grievance disputes.  On behalf of the Department directs  the preparation of proposals and counter proposals for the  settlement of such disputes and rejects or accepts suggested  binding agreements, settlements and final understandings.Directs the Department's role in hearings before arbitrators  and hearing officers of the Public Employment Relations  Commission.Directs the Department's preparation for grievances and  disciplinary arbitration hearings.Directs the conference appeal process related to the  termination of unclassified and provisional employees as set  forth on the applicable State wide unit agreements or  contracts.Supervises the work operations and/or functional programs  and has responsibility for effectively recommending the  hiring, firing, promoting, demoting and/or disciplining of  employees.Assures appropriate and necessary training is provided to  components of the Department in the administration of  State wide unit agreements and contracts.Assures that the Department disciplinary action policies,  practices and procedures are followed.Directs the planning, research and preparation of employee  relations programs.Directs the preparation and promulgation of directives,  circulars, and bulletins which establish policies,  procedures, and practices pertaining to grievance and  disciplinary procedures.Directs the coordination and monitoring of all grievance  processing at the levels within the institutions and  agencies.Makes continuous reviews of Department grievance procedures.Sees that assistance is provided to the several institutions  and agencies in employee relations matters.Reviews and devises means and methods of improving working  conditions and alleviating sources of employee grievances.Plans, organizes and directs surveys and studies and  interprets varied types of law policies and data.Acts as the representative of the Department at meetings,  conferences and hearings.Drafts extensive official correspondence.Prepares and directs the preparation of clear, sound,  accurate and informative reports and summaries containing  findings, conclusions and recommendations.Directs the establishment of maintenance of records and  files.Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic  and/or manual recording and information systems used by  the agency, office, or related units. REQUIREMENTS:NOTE: Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.    Ten (10) years of administrative experience in employee relations work in a large organization, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and six (6) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.ORPossession of a Master's degree from an accredited college or university in Business Administration, Public Administration, personnel administration, or labor relations; and five (5) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, three (3) years of which shall have been in a supervisory capacity.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgment and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIESKnowledge of regulations, policies, procedures, organizational  structure and operations of the Department of Human Services.Knowledge of the provisions of Chapter 303 (the New Jersey  Employer Employee Relations Act and its relation to  programs, policies and operations.Knowledge of the problems which arise in the interpretation  of contracts to management and employee organizations, the  implementation of changes and adjustments to practices and  the policing of  grievance machinery.Knowledge of the policies, practices, procedures and other  matters pertaining to the Office of Employee Relations.Knowledge of the rules, regulations, policies, standards,  and procedures of the New Jersey Department of Personnel  and of the New Jersey Civil Service law as it relates to the  State service.Knowledge of Departmental grievance policies, practices and  procedures.Knowledge of public and employee relations personnel  administration, personnel principles and practices.Knowledge of labor mediation and arbitration methods.Ability to organize assigned personnel administrative work  and develop appropriate work procedures.Ability to read and interpret basic legislation, rules, and  regulations and apply them to specific situations.Ability to recognize and analyze the varied employee  relations and personnel problems of a large and complex  State department and develop appropriate working procedures.Ability to assign and instruct employees in the employee  relations program and supervise the performance of their  work.Ability to work harmoniously with associates, Commissioner's  Office and staff, Division Directors, and others and with  that portion of the public interested in or concerned with  the programs and complex responsibilities of the Department  and its several subdivisions.Ability to establish and maintain cooperative working  relationships with the representatives of other State  Departments and Offices and employees organizations.Ability to deal effectively with Department employees and   institution and agency officers in employee relations  matters, to make  and/or direct surveys and studies, to  implement the resulting data, and to draw conclusions.Ability to direct the smooth handling of varied types of  complex transactions.Ability to prepare and direct the preparation of extensive  official correspondence.Ability to prepare and direct the preparation of clear,  sound,  accurate and informative statistical, financial and  other reports, analyses and summaries containing findings,  conclusions and formal  recommendations.Ability to provide work assignments, instructions and  training to individuals and supervise the performance of  their work.Ability to serve as Departmental representative and  participate as required in meetings, conferences and  hearings.Ability to provide information, clarification,  interpretation and advice concerning policies, procedures,  practices and other matters pertaining to Chapter 303.Ability to propose needed changes in employee relations  policies, act as liaison between employee organizations and  provide a constant review and assessment of proposals and  developments.Ability to direct the establishment and maintenance of  records and files.Ability to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and information systems used by the agency,  office, or related units.Ability to read, write, speak, understand, and communicate  in English sufficiently to perform duties of this position.  American Sign Language or Braille may also be considered as  acceptable forms of communication.Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as  long as they can perform essential functions of the job  after reasonable accommodation is made to their known  limitations.  If the accommodation cannot be made because it  would cause the employer undue hardship, such persons may  not be eligible.CODES:     35/M35 - 63269     MCK     09/18/04

