REALTY SPECIALIST 1 TRANSPORTATION    DEFINITION:Under the close supervision of a Realty Specialist 3, Transportation or  Realty Specialist 4, Transportation, performs the work involved in conducting  negotiations, relocation, property management, project programming,  administrative and the laws and principles of Eminent Domain activities  associated with the purchase and disposition of real property; does other  related duties as assigned.NOTE: The examples of work for this title are for illustrative purposes  only.  A particular position using this title may not perform all duties listed in this  job specification. Conversely, all duties performed on the job may not be listed. EXAMPLES OF WORK:Conducts negotiations with property owners, agents for owners and owner's  counsel for necessary property rights and makes personal service of legal  documents.Prepares contracts for the purchase of real property and provides  explanations to property owners regarding the meaning of clauses  contained in agreements and legal pleadings.Provides relocation advisory assistance to occupants and assists occupants  in making application for relocation payments.Interprets Right of Way and construction plans to describe and respond to  owner's questions regarding the proposed property acquisition.Reviews the Access cutout and compares cutout to Individual Parcel Map.Reviews environmental reports or letters.  Explains to owners the impact  contamination may have on the valuation of the property.Investigates and clarifies problem areas with respect to determination of  state real property ownership, title searches, department jurisdiction, and  property boundaries.Aids the unit supervisor in gathering, interpreting, and correlating  miscellaneous state and local real property and/or design/construction  project data and prepares factual reports of findings.Provides information to other state agencies, local governments, and the  general public on matters relating to state owned or leased real property  and design/construction projects.Participates in developing and maintaining an inventory of suitable properties  available, and performs some market research analysis to identify suitable  properties using market surveys, published and computerized information  sources, and multimedia advertising, contacting real estate broker, owners,  or agents, and making personal site evaluations to locate potential leased  space for use by state agencies.Conducts negotiations pursuant to the standards set forth in the  Administrative/Legal Settlement Authorization Schedule.  Conducts on-site inspections of real property and secures ownership/tenancy  data relevant to the residential or commercial occupants. Prepares site  occupancy surveys and workable relocation assistance plans.Investigates the real estate market and locates information pertaining to  comparable sales and leases, which provide indicators of current property  values.Responds to requests from state and local officials regarding state real  property matters.Conducts investigations of title to real property. Develops information  regarding tax assessments and encumbrances on the title of real property.Assists staff appraisers in preparing estimates of the cost to acquire real  property for proposed transportation improvements.Provides assistance to Deputy Attorneys General in condemnation proceedings.May testify as a witness in condemnation hearings and trials.Will be required to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual  recording and computerized information systems used by the agency,  office or related units. REQUIREMENTS:NOTE:Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.  Five (5) years of professional experience in any phase of Right of Way work subject to the Federal Highway Funding Reimbursement Program (e.g. appraisal, negotiations, relocation, property management or programming and admistration).ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and one (1) year of the above-mentioned professional experience.NOTE: "Professional experience" refers to work that is analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range of basic knowledge of the profession's concepts and practices; and is performed with the authority to act and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointees will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.KNOWLEDGE AND ABILITIES:Knowledge of the problems involved in appraising real estate and  negotiating for its purchase.Knowledge of procedures for preparing real estate contracts.Knowledge of the procedures to be followed in investigating and  determining land values and preparing estimates of the cost of  improvements on the land.Knowledge of the types of appraisal methods available.Knowledge of general engineering concepts utilized in the preparation  of specialist reports.Knowledge of the basic Access Code process as implemented by  the State.  Knowledge of the interaction between the Access Code and the  Acquisition of Right of Way.Knowledge of and familiarity with the basic legal terms and concepts  prevailing in real estate law, including the laws and principles of  Eminent Domain, and their application to the work of the bureau.Ability to communicate effectively with property owners regarding the  purchase of real property.Ability to analyze the problems involved in appraising the current and  potential market value of real estate.  Ability to negotiate for the purchase  of real estate.Ability to explain the basics behind the environmental report.Ability to investigate problem areas with respect to determination of  state real property ownership, title searches, department jurisdiction,  and property boundaries.Ability to interpret legal agreements and descriptions of property.Ability to correlate data pertaining to sales and use it to identify trends  affecting property values.Ability to conduct basic investigations of titles to land and encumbrances.Ability to prepare cost estimates and specifications.Ability to read and analyze construction plans and determine their  probable effect upon land values and damage to property.Ability to maintain information in mapped and tabular form for state real  property holdings in New Jersey.Ability to provide information to other state agencies, local governments,  and the general public on matters relating to state owned or leased  real property and design/construction projects.Ability to comprehend basic law and regulations pertaining to the purchase  of land for highway uses and to interpret them to laymen, property owners,  and others.Ability to organize and accomplish assigned work.Ability to understand and interpret contracts agreements and plans.Ability to work constructively and cooperatively with staff and to establish  and maintain productive contacts with property owners, the general public,  and the representatives of county and municipal jurisdictions.Ability to successfully complete a formalized course of instruction concerning  real property acquisition techniques.Ability to prepare clear, concise, accurate, and informative reports, containing  findings, conclusions, and recommendations.Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual recording  and information systems used by the agency, office or related units.Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in English sufficiently  to perform the duties of this position. American Sign Language or Braille may  also be considered as acceptable forms of communication.Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long as they  can perform essential functions of the job with or without reasonable  accommodation.  If the accommodation cannot be made because it would  cause the employer undue hardship, such persons may not be eligible.CODES:  18/P18  - 57062                MER                         04/24/2010

