SUPERVISOR, CASH RECEIPTS AND DEPOSITS 65974DEFINITIONUnder the direction of a supervisory officer in a State department or agency, supervises personnel  responsible for the receiving, safeguarding, recording and depositing of all remittances received in  the form of cash, checks, and money orders; does related work as required.  EXAMPLES OF WORK  Supervises, the preparation of clear, sound, accurate and informative reports for funds receipt.  control purposes and furnishes the data to the Receivables Control Unit, the Office of the Budget  and the Accounting Records Unit for required recordkeeping and financial statements.Supervises the preparation and control of the bank transmittal for funds deposited in accounts  controlled by the Department or agency and of the transmittal of funds which are sent to the  Department of Treasury.Maintains records and fifes according to good accounting procedures.Devise methods and procedures for the efficient and expedient processing of returned tomb.Coordinates and expedites the flow of work resulting from peak periods during the month of  remittances to meet established time schedules.Prepares the more difficult and complex technical correspondence on remittance matters and  inquiries.Assigns and instructs employees of the unit and supervises and evaluates the performance of their  work.Supervises the work operations and/or functional programs and has responsibility for employee  evaluations and for effectively recommending the hiring, firing, promoting, demoting and/or  disciplining of employees.Meets with hank representatives when problems arise pertaining to deposit of and the accounting  fur remittances, the processing of dishonored checks, and other related financial matters.Confers with vendors, donors, and clients on matters pertaining to funds collected by the  Department or Agency.Works directly with Treasury Department when discrepancies occur in deposits made by  Department or Agency.Appears as witness on behalf of the State in Court and at Administrative Hearings.Provides training to employees supervised.May he required to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual recording and  information systems used by the agency, office or related units.REQUIREMENTS:NOTE:Applicants must meet one of the following or a combination of both experience and education. Thirty (30) semester-hour credits are equal to one (1) year of relevant experience.Six (6) years of professional experience in the receiving, safeguarding, and accounting of large sums of money, one (1) year of which shall have included supervisory responsibility.ORPossession of a bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university; and two (2) years of the above-mentioned professional experience, one (1) year of which shall have included supervisory responsibility.NOTE:"Professional experience refers to work that is creative, analytical, evaluative, and interpretive; requires a range and depth of specialized knowledge of the profession's principles, concepts, theories, and practices; and is performed with the authority to act according to one's own judgement and make accurate and informed decisions.LICENSE:Appointee will be required to possess a driver's license valid in New Jersey only if the operation of a vehicle, rather than employee mobility, is necessary to perform the essential duties of the position.Knowledges and AbilitiesConsiderable knowledge of the problems involved in supervising a staff in the receipt,  safeguarding, and deposit of remittances made by vendors.Considerable knowledge of the problems which arise in conferring with vendors and/or their  representatives with reference to remittance matters and related problems in vendor accounts.Considerable knowledge of modern business methods and procedures and their application.Basic knowledge of the principles and procedures of accounting and ability to learn to use  electronic data processing systems.Basic knowledge of the procedures useful in compiling training material and in giving training to  employees as may be required.Ability to assign and instruct unit employees, provide them with advice and assistance when  difficult and unusual problems arise, and check their work to see that proper procedures are  followed, that reasonable standards of workmanship and output are maintained, and that desired  objectives are achieved.Ability to coordinate the flow of work resulting from peak periods in order to meet established time  schedules.Ability to analyze the more difficult and complex problems which arise in accounts in order to  correct or adjust discrepancies.Ability to work with associates, subordinates, and with individuals and groups concerned with the  collection provisions of the Department or Agency.Ability to utilize approved training procedures and methods and to train unit employees .Ability to draft and supervise the preparation of correspondence concerned with remittances.Ability to prepare clear, sound, accurate and informative financial, statistical and other statements  and reports of unit activities containing findings, conclusions and recommendations.Ability to supervise the maintenance of extensive records and files.Ability to learn to utilize various types of electronic and/or manual recording and information  systems used by the agency, office or related units.Ability to read, write, speak, understand, or communicate in English sufficiently to perform the  duties of this position. American Sign Language or braille may also be considered as acceptable  forms of communication.Persons with mental or physical disabilities are eligible as long as they can perform the essential  functions of the job after reasonable accommodation in made to their known limitations. If the  accommodation cannot be made because it would cause the employer undue hardship, such  persons may not be eligible.This job specification is applicable to the following title code:JobSpecCodeVariantState,Local orCommonClass ofServiceWorkWeekStateClassCodeLocalClassCodeSalaryRangeNote65974SC3522N/AR21-This job specification is for state government use only.Salary range is only applicable to state government.Local salaries are established by individual local jurisdictions. 12/8/86

